Home Credit Default Risk (HCDR)¶

The course project is based on the Home Credit Default Risk (HCDR) Kaggle Competition. The goal of this project is to predict whether or not a client will repay a loan. In order to make sure that people who struggle to get loans due to insufficient or non-existent credit histories have a positive loan experience, Home Credit makes use of a variety of alternative data--including telco and transactional information--to predict their clients' repayment abilities.

Dataset analysis¶

Here we make use of data that has been already downloaded from the kaggle project and save it into variables so that visualization and analysis of data becomes easy

Home Credit is a non-banking financial institution, founded in 1997 in the Czech Republic.

The company operates in 14 countries (including United States, Russia, Kazahstan, Belarus, China, India) and focuses on lending primarily to people with little or no credit history which will either not obtain loans or became victims of untrustworthly lenders.

Home Credit group has over 29 million customers, total assests of 21 billions Euro, over 160 millions loans, with the majority in Asia and and almost half of them in China (as of 19-05-2018).

While Home Credit is currently using various statistical and machine learning methods to make these predictions, they're challenging Kagglers to help them unlock the full potential of their data. Doing so will ensure that clients capable of repayment are not rejected and that loans are given with a principal, maturity, and repayment calendar that will empower their clients to be successful.

Data files overview¶

There are 7 different sources of data:

  • application_train/application_test (307k rows, and 48k rows): the main training and testing data with information about each loan application at Home Credit. Every loan has its own row and is identified by the feature SK_ID_CURR. The training application data comes with the TARGET indicating 0: the loan was repaid or 1: the loan was not repaid. The target variable defines if the client had payment difficulties meaning he/she had late payment more than X days on at least one of the first Y installments of the loan. Such case is marked as 1 while other all other cases as 0.

  • bureau (1.7 Million rows): data concerning client's previous credits from other financial institutions. Each previous credit has its own row in bureau, but one loan in the application data can have multiple previous credits.

  • bureau_balance (27 Million rows): monthly data about the previous credits in bureau. Each row is one month of a previous credit, and a single previous credit can have multiple rows, one for each month of the credit length.

  • previous_application (1.6 Million rows): previous applications for loans at Home Credit of clients who have loans in the application data. Each current loan in the application data can have multiple previous loans. Each previous application has one row and is identified by the feature SK_ID_PREV.

  • POS_CASH_BALANCE (10 Million rows): monthly data about previous point of sale or cash loans clients have had with Home Credit. Each row is one month of a previous point of sale or cash loan, and a single previous loan can have many rows.

  • credit_card_balance: monthly data about previous credit cards clients have had with Home Credit. Each row is one month of a credit card balance, and a single credit card can have many rows.

  • installments_payment (13.6 Million rows): payment history for previous loans at Home Credit. There is one row for every made payment and one row for every missed payment.

def drop_columns_by_missing_ratio(data, pct_missing):
    """
    Drops columns from the DataFrame if their missing value ratio is greater than pct_missing.

    Parameters:
    data (DataFrame): The pandas DataFrame to modify.
    pct_missing (float): The threshold for the missing value ratio. Columns with a missing value ratio higher than this will be dropped.

    Returns:
    DataFrame: The modified DataFrame with specified columns dropped.
    """
    # Calculate the missing ratio for each column
    missing_ratio = data.isnull().sum() / len(data) * 100

    # Find columns where the missing ratio is greater than pct_missing
    columns_to_drop = missing_ratio[missing_ratio > pct_missing].index

    # Drop these columns
    data_dropped = data.drop(columns=columns_to_drop)

    return data_dropped

def list_columns_with_few_unique_values(df, max_unique_values=5):
    """
    Lists all columns in the DataFrame that have less than a specified number of unique values,
    along with those unique values.

    Parameters:
    df (DataFrame): The pandas DataFrame to analyze.
    max_unique_values (int): The maximum number of unique values a column should have to be included.

    Returns:
    dict: A dictionary where keys are column names and values are lists of unique values in those columns.
    """
    columns_with_few_unique_values = {}

    for column in df.columns:
        unique_values = df[column].unique()
        if len(unique_values) < max_unique_values:
            columns_with_few_unique_values[column] = unique_values

    return columns_with_few_unique_values

def convert_to_categorical(df, max_unique_values=5):
    """
    Converts columns in the DataFrame to categorical if they are numerical and 
    have fewer than a specified number of unique values.

    Parameters:
    df (DataFrame): The pandas DataFrame to modify.
    max_unique_values (int): The maximum number of unique values a column should have to be converted.

    Returns:
    DataFrame: The modified DataFrame with specified columns converted to categorical.
    """
    for column in df.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns:
        if df[column].nunique() < max_unique_values:
            df[column] = df[column].astype(str).astype('category')

    return df

def list_and_count_column_types(df):
    """
    Lists and counts the numerical and categorical columns in a pandas DataFrame.

    Parameters:
    df (DataFrame): The pandas DataFrame to analyze.

    Returns:
    tuple: A tuple containing two lists (numerical columns, categorical columns) and two integers (count of numerical columns, count of categorical columns).
    """
    # Selecting numerical columns
    numerical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns.tolist()
    num_numerical_cols = len(numerical_cols)

    # Selecting categorical columns
    # Assuming 'object' and 'category' dtypes as categorical
    categorical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns.tolist()
    num_categorical_cols = len(categorical_cols)
    return numerical_cols, categorical_cols, num_numerical_cols, num_categorical_cols

from scipy.stats import pearsonr

def calculate_correlations(df, target_column):
    """
    Calculates correlations of each column in the DataFrame with a specified target column,
    excluding rows where either the column or the target has missing values.
    Returns the top 10 and bottom 10 correlations.

    Parameters:
    df (DataFrame): The pandas DataFrame to analyze.
    target_column (str): The name of the target column.

    Returns:
    dict: Two dictionaries containing the top 10 and bottom 10 correlations.
    """
    correlations = {}

    # Ensure the target column is numeric
    if df[target_column].dtype not in [np.float64, np.int64]:
        df[target_column] = pd.to_numeric(df[target_column], errors='coerce')

    for col in df.columns:
        if col != target_column and df[col].dtype in [np.float64, np.int64]:
            # Drop rows where either the column or the target column is missing
            temp_df = df[[col, target_column]].dropna()
            
            # Calculate correlation if both columns have more than 1 unique value
            if len(temp_df[col].unique()) > 1 and len(temp_df[target_column].unique()) > 1:
                corr, _ = pearsonr(temp_df[col], temp_df[target_column])
                correlations[col] = corr

    # Sort correlations by absolute value and get top 10 and bottom 10
    top_10 = dict(sorted(correlations.items(), key=lambda item: abs(item[1]), reverse=True)[:10])
    bottom_10 = dict(sorted(correlations.items(), key=lambda item: abs(item[1]))[:10])

    return top_10, bottom_10

# Usage example:
# top_10_correlations, bottom_10_correlations = calculate_correlations(df, 'TARGET')
calculate_correlations(app_train_df,'TARGET')

import pandas as pd
import scipy.stats as ss

def calculate_categorical_associations(df, target_column):
    """
    Calculates the association (using Chi-Square test of independence) of each categorical 
    variable in the DataFrame with a specified target column, excluding rows where 
    either the variable or the target has missing values. Returns variables with p-values less than 0.05.

    Parameters:
    df (DataFrame): The pandas DataFrame to analyze.
    target_column (str): The name of the target column.

    Returns:
    dict: A dictionary containing variables with p-values less than 0.05.
    """
    significant_associations = {}

    for col in df.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns:
        if col != target_column:
            # Drop rows where either the column or the target column is missing
            temp_df = df[[col, target_column]].dropna()

            # Calculate Chi-Square test of independence
            chi2, p, _, _ = ss.chi2_contingency(pd.crosstab(temp_df[col], temp_df[target_column]))

            # Check for significance
            if p < 0.05:
                significant_associations[col] = p

    return significant_associations

# Usage example:
# significant_assoc = calculate_categorical_associations(df, 'TARGET')
calculate_categorical_associations(app_train_df,'TARGET')

def nullColsDropping(table, threshold):
    df = dataDict[table]
    null_df = pd.DataFrame(countNulls(table)*100/df.shape[0])
    miss_data_col=null_df[null_df[0]>threshold].index
    new_df = df.drop(columns=miss_data_col)
    return new_df

def df_aggregate_features(features, agg_ops, tableName):
    appsDF = dataDict[tableName]

    b=pd.Index(c).append(a)
    val_res.columns=b
    display(val_res)
    return val_res

from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin

# Create pipeline for aggregate features
class prevAppsFeaturesAggregater(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, features=None):  # no *args or **kwargs
        self.features = features
        self.features_agg = {}
        for i in features:
            # Corrected string interpolation using f-strings
            self.features_agg[i] = [(f"{i}_{method}", method) for method in ["min", "max", "mean"]]
        print(self.features_agg)

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        final_res = X.groupby(["SK_ID_CURR"]).agg(self.features_agg)
        final_res.columns = final_res.columns.droplevel()
        final_res = final_res.reset_index(level=["SK_ID_CURR"])
        final_res['range_AMT_APPLICATION'] = final_res['AMT_APPLICATION_max'] - final_res['AMT_APPLICATION_min']
        return final_res  # return dataframe with the join key "SK_ID_CURR"

Merging Tables to include secondary features¶

Application train features:¶

The additional attributes incorporated into the "application_train" dataset provide valuable insights for lenders to evaluate a borrower's loan repayment capacity. The "CREDIT_TO_INCOME_RATIO" assesses the ratio between the borrower's income and the requested loan amount. Meanwhile, the "ANNUITY_TO_INCOME_RATIO" evaluates the ratio between the borrower's current debt and their income. The inclusion of the "AGE" attribute provides information about the borrower's age, essential for legal considerations in employment. Additionally, the "EMPLOYMENT_LENGTH" feature indicates the duration of the borrower's employment tenure, offering insights into their work stability.

Bureau dataset features:¶

The code aims to generate three features crucial for assessing credit risk. Initially, "RATIO_DEBT_TO_CREDIT" computes the debt-to-credit ratio for each loan, offering insights into a borrower's debt levels. Next, "CREDIT_LENGTH" evaluates the duration a borrower has been using credit, reflecting their experience managing credit accounts. Lastly, "MAX_OVERDUE_DAYS" calculates the maximum days a borrower has exceeded payment deadlines, signaling their ability to fulfill debts promptly. These features unveil a borrower's creditworthiness, enabling lenders to discern risks and make informed decisions about credit approvals and risk management strategies.

Credit_card_balance features:¶

The discussed quartet of features pertains to a borrower's credit behavior, aiding in the identification of individuals potentially struggling with debt repayment. The balance-to-limit ratio gauges the ratio of a borrower's credit limit utilized, while the limit reached count tracks instances when they've hit the credit ceiling. Additionally, the minimum payment late count tallies delayed minimum payments, and the average credit used per month calculates the monthly credit utilization average. These characteristics collectively assist in identifying borrowers prone to defaulting on loans, enhancing a model's precision in predicting loan defaults..

Installment_Payments features:¶

In the updated installment payments data, new attributes introduced encompass payment_percentage, payment_difference, and days_past_due. Payment_percentage gauges the proportion of the installment sum paid by the borrower, whereas payment_difference assesses the variance between the scheduled payment and the actual amount paid. Days_past_due quantifies the duration an installment payment remains overdue. These attributes aid the model in pinpointing borrowers facing challenges in timely payments, potentially indicating a risk of loan default.

Pos_cash_balance features:¶

The attribute "PREVIOUS_CASH_LOANS" tallies the count of prior cash loans taken by a customer, while "late_payments" determines the instances of delayed repayments in previous loans. Additionally, "AVG_DAYS_PAST_DUE" computes the average overdue days across a borrower's earlier loans. These attributes support the model in recognizing borrowers who might encounter challenges in loan repayment, considering aspects like down payment size, applicant income, and loan interest rates.

Previous_application_features:¶

The initial attribute, "LOAN_TO_VALUE_RATIO," computes the relationship between the loan amount and the asset's value being acquired. Meanwhile, the second attribute, "DOWN_PAYMENT_RATIO," determines the proportion of the down payment compared to the loan amount. The third feature, "INSTALLMENT_RATIO," measures the installment amount in relation to the loan amount. The integration of these attributes offers valuable insights into the financial standing of borrowers and enhances the model's accuracy during its design process

# Convert categorical features to numerical approximations (via pipeline)
class ClaimAttributesAdder(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def fit(self, K, y=None):
        return self
    def transform(self, K, y=None): 
        index_dict = {'0': 0, '1-2': 2, '3-4': 4, '5+': 6}
        dict_loss = {'1 day': 1, '2 days': 2, '3 days': 3, '4 days': 4, '5 days': 5, '6 days': 6,
          '1- 2 weeks': 11, '2- 4 weeks': 21, '4- 8 weeks': 42, '26+ weeks': 180}
        K['PayDelay'] = K['PayDelay'].apply(lambda x: int(x) if x != '162+' else int(162))
        K['DSFS'] = K['DSFS'].apply(lambda x: None if pd.isnull(x) else int(x[0]) + 1)
        K['CharlsonIndex'] = K['CharlsonIndex'].apply(lambda x: index_dict[x])
        K['LengthOfStay'] = K['LengthOfStay'].apply(lambda x: None if pd.isnull(x) else dict_loss[x])
        return K

class DataFrameSelector(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, attribute_names):
        self.attribute_names = attribute_names
    def fit(self, K, y=None):
        return self
    def transform(self, K):
        return K[self.attribute_names].values

combined_features = list(df_sampled.columns)
print(df_sampled["AMT_BALANCE_max"].dtype)
combined_features.remove("TARGET")
num_features = [i for i in combined_features if df_sampled[i].dtype in [np.float64, np.int64]]
cat_features = [j for j in combined_features if j not in num_features]

numerical_attribs = []
num_pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('selector', DataFrameSelector(numerical_attribs)),('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')),('std_scaler', StandardScaler()),])

catogorical_attribs = []

df_sample = df_sampled[combined_features]
for k1 in df_sample:
    if(df_sample[k1].dtype == np.float64 or df_sample[k1].dtype == np.int64):
         numerical_attribs.append(k1)
    else:
         catogorical_attribs.append(k1)


print("catogorical_attribs",catogorical_attribs)
cat_pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('selector', DataFrameSelector(catogorical_attribs)),
        ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='constant', fill_value='most_frequent')),
        ('ohe', OneHotEncoder(sparse_output=False, handle_unknown="ignore"))
    ])

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer([('num', num_pipeline, num_features),('cat', cat_pipeline, cat_features)])

data_prep_pipeline = FeatureUnion(transformer_list=[("num_pipeline", num_pipeline),("cat_pipeline", cat_pipeline),])

from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
import re
import time

# defining pipeline:
clf_logistic_regression_pipe = Pipeline([("data_pipe", preprocessor),
    ("logistic_regression", LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000))])

# parameters:
hyper_parameters = {'logistic_regression__C': [1.0, 10.0, 100.0, 1000.0, 10000.0],
                     'logistic_regression__penalty': ['none', 'l1', 'l2'],
                     'logistic_regression__solver': ['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'liblinear', 'sag', 'saga']}

from sklearn.neural_network import MLPClassifier
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, roc_auc_score
import time
import pandas as pd

# defining pipeline:
clf_mlp_pipe = Pipeline([("data_pipe", preprocessor),
                         ("mlp", MLPClassifier(max_iter=1000))])

# parameters:
hyper_parameters = {
    'mlp__hidden_layer_sizes': [(50,), (100,), (50, 50)],
    'mlp__activation': ['tanh', 'relu'],
    'mlp__solver': ['sgd', 'adam'],
    'mlp__alpha': [0.0001, 0.001],
    'mlp__learning_rate': ['constant', 'adaptive']
}

# Training the model
begin_time = time.time()

# Gridsearch:
clf_gridsearch = GridSearchCV(clf_mlp_pipe, param_grid=hyper_parameters, cv=3, scoring='accuracy')
clf_gridsearch.fit(X_train, y_train)

train_time = time.time() - begin_time
print("Best parameters of the model are:")
print(clf_gridsearch.best_params_)

# Testing the model
model_mlp = clf_gridsearch.best_estimator_

begin_time = time.time()
y_pred = model_mlp.predict(X_test)
test_time = time.time() - begin_time

exp_name = "MLP+hyperparameter"

Test_Acc = accuracy_score(y_test, model_mlp.predict(X_test))

from sklearn.ensemble import VotingClassifier
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, roc_auc_score
import pandas as pd
import time

# Define individual pipelines with their best hyperparameters
clf_random_forest_pipe = Pipeline([
    ("data_pipe", preprocessor),
    ("random_forest", RandomForestClassifier(
        max_depth= 10, min_samples_leaf= 1, min_samples_split= 2, n_estimators= 10
    ))
])

clf_logistic_regression_pipe = Pipeline([
    ("data_pipe", preprocessor),
    ("logistic_regression", LogisticRegression(
        C= 1.0, penalty= 'l1', solver= 'liblinear'
    ))
])

clf_decision_tree_pipe = Pipeline([
    ("data_pipe", preprocessor),
    ("decision_tree", DecisionTreeClassifier(
        criterion= 'gini', max_depth= 10, max_features= 'log2', min_samples_leaf= 4, min_samples_split= 10, 
        splitter= 'random'
    ))
])

clf_mlp_pipe = Pipeline([
    ("data_pipe", preprocessor),
    ("mlp", MLPClassifier(
        activation= 'tanh', alpha= 0.0001, hidden_layer_sizes= (100,), learning_rate= 'adaptive', solver= 'sgd'
    ))
])

# Define the VotingClassifier
ensemble_model = VotingClassifier(
    estimators=[
        ('random_forest', clf_random_forest_pipe),
        ('logistic_regression', clf_logistic_regression_pipe),
        ('decision_tree', clf_decision_tree_pipe),
        ('mlp', clf_mlp_pipe)
    ],
    voting='soft'  # Use 'soft' for probabilities or 'hard' for labels
)

# Train the ensemble model
begin_time = time.time()
ensemble_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
train_time = time.time() - begin_time

y_pred = ensemble_model.predict(X_test)

Abstract¶

The project aims to develop a machine learning model to predict loan defaults. In this phase, we focus on enhancing model performance through feature engineering, pipelining, and hyperparameter tuning. Initially, we preprocess the data by removing features with excessive missing values or irrelevant information and then merge separate feature tables. This approach enables the incorporation of secondary features such as credit length and loan-to-value ratio, which are critical for understanding correlations with the target variable.

We explore multiple pipelines to test various models, employing grid search for hyperparameter tuning. This exhaustive search evaluates every combination of parameters to ensure optimal model performance. The models implemented include Random Forest, Decision Tree, Logistic Regression, and Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP). For further enhancement, we employ an ensemble voting technique to combine predictions from multiple models, improving accuracy and robustness. Both hard voting (majority class selection) and soft voting (average of predicted probabilities) are explored.

Evaluation metrics such as accuracy and Area Under the Curve (AUC) are utilized to assess model performance comprehensively, ensuring a reliable prediction framework for loan defaults.

Gantt Chart¶

Data Description¶

In this project we will be using the data from Kaggle on Home credit Default Risk. Kaggle dataset link: https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/home-credit-default-risk/data

The Home Credit Default Risk dataset from Kaggle consists of multiple tables containing various financial and demographic information:

application_{train|test}.csv: The primary table, detailing loan applications. In the training set, the TARGET variable indicates whether a loan was repaid on time (0) or defaulted (1).

POS_CASH_balance.csv: Monthly balance data for point-of-sale (POS) and cash loans, with each entry corresponding to a specific month.

bureau.csv: Details about loans taken by the applicant from other financial institutions, including loan types and repayment histories.

bureau_balance.csv: Monthly status information for loans listed in the bureau.csv dataset.

credit_card_balance.csv: Information about credit card balances and transactions, capturing metrics like payment history and credit limits.

installments_payments.csv: Historical records of installment payments for past loans, including payment dates and amounts.

previous_application.csv: Data on prior loan applications, including outcomes and associated credit terms.

This diverse data collection provides a comprehensive view of an applicant's financial behavior, which is crucial for assessing creditworthiness.

Feature Engineering¶

This step involves gathering information on null values across all secondary tables, identifying columns with nulls and their respective percentages. Then, columns with over 50% nulls in all tables are removed, streamlining the data by eliminating less relevant or redundant information that might not significantly contribute to predictive accuracy. Additionally, aggregation operations like min, max, mean, sum, and standard deviation are applied to specific columns in these tables, extracting valuable features for training ML models. These modified tables are subsequently merged with the main application train and test datasets, forming a comprehensive dataset for training and testing ML models.

During the Feature Engineering phase, various tasks were undertaken to prep the data for model training. These tasks included identifying null values, discarding columns with excessive null values, and executing aggregation operations to create new features.

A prominent feature introduced was the count of prior loans taken out by applicants, directly appended to the application dataset. This addition could be insightful since past loan history might hint at repayment capabilities.

For other tables, we engineered new features by performing aggregation operations like mean, max, and standard deviation. To gauge these features' impact on the model, multiple experiments were conducted using diverse feature-algorithm combinations. Overall, these new features exhibited a positive influence, enhancing both accuracy and AUC scores.

We opted for the strategy of integrating new features through aggregation operations and merging secondary tables due to their proven effectiveness in various real-world applications. Leveraging domain knowledge, we cherry-picked features we believed could offer predictive insights into loan default risks.

In essence, our Feature Engineering phase succeeded in crafting new features that notably boosted our model's performance. We consider this approach of meticulous feature selection and engineering a valuable asset for constructing robust ML models.

Model Pipelining¶

This diagram illustrates a structured approach to building a machine learning pipeline for classification tasks, incorporating both numerical and categorical data. The process begins with the input data, which includes attributes of both types. These attributes are processed separately through designated pipelines for numerical and categorical features before being merged into a unified preprocessing workflow.

The numerical pipeline handles missing values and feature scaling. Missing numerical data is addressed using imputation, where null values are replaced with the mean of the respective feature. Afterward, feature scaling is applied using a standard scaler to normalize the numerical attributes, ensuring that all numerical features are on a similar scale, which is critical for many machine learning algorithms.

The categorical pipeline addresses categorical variables. Missing values in these features are filled using a constant value, such as 'missing.' This step ensures that no information is lost during preprocessing. Next, one-hot encoding is applied to transform categorical variables into binary representations that machine learning models can interpret. The handle_unknown='ignore' parameter is used during encoding to prevent errors when encountering unseen categories during inference.

Both pipelines—the numerical and categorical ones—are combined into a data preparation pipeline (data_prep_pipeline). This unified pipeline ensures consistent preprocessing of all input data, making the workflow reproducible and scalable. Once the data is preprocessed, it is passed to a Logistic Regression model for training and prediction. Logistic Regression is used as the classifier in this pipeline to predict the target variable.

The final step involves classification, where the trained Logistic Regression model predicts the class labels for new data. This modular and systematic approach ensures that the preprocessing and modeling steps are seamlessly integrated, resulting in a robust and efficient machine learning workflow.

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Once we created the pipeline, we moved on to choosing the best parameters for our models. Here's a detailed explanation of the hyperparameters used and the best values chosen for each of the models:

Logistic Regression¶

C: Inverse of regularization strength. Smaller values specify stronger regularization. Values used: [1.0, 10.0, 100.0, 1000.0, 10000.0]. Best value: 1.0.

penalty: Type of regularization (e.g., L1 or L2). L1 can lead to sparse models with few coefficients. Values used: ['none', 'l1', 'l2']. Best value: 'l1'.

solver: Algorithm for optimization (e.g., 'liblinear' for small datasets). Values used: ['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'liblinear', 'sag', 'saga']. Best value: 'liblinear'.

Random Forest Classifier¶

n_estimators: Number of trees in the forest. More trees can improve accuracy but increase computation time. Values used: [10, 50, 100]. Best value: 10.

max_depth: Maximum depth of each tree. Controls complexity and risk of overfitting. Values used: [None, 10, 50, 100]. Best value: 10.

min_samples_split: Minimum number of samples required to split a node. Helps prevent overfitting. Values used: [2, 5, 10]. Best value: 2.

min_samples_leaf: Minimum number of samples required at a leaf node. Smaller values can lead to overfitting. Values used: [1, 2, 4]. Best value: 1.

Decision Tree Classifier¶

criterion: Function to measure quality of a split (e.g., 'gini' or 'entropy'). Values used: ['gini', 'entropy']. Best value: 'gini'.

splitter: Strategy for splitting nodes ('best' or 'random'). Values used: ['best', 'random']. Best value: 'random'.

max_depth: Maximum depth of the tree to control model complexity. Values used: [None, 10, 50, 100]. Best value: 10.

min_samples_split: Minimum samples for a node split to prevent overfitting. Values used: [2, 5, 10]. Best value: 10.

min_samples_leaf: Minimum samples at a leaf node to reduce overfitting. Values used: [1, 2, 4]. Best value: 4.

max_features: Number of features to consider when looking for the best split. Values used: ['auto', 'sqrt', 'log2']. Best value: 'log2'.

Multilayer Perceptron¶

hidden_layer_sizes: Number of neurons in hidden layers. Determines network capacity and complexity. Values used: [(50,), (100,), (50, 50)]. Best value: (100,).

activation: Activation function for neurons (e.g., 'tanh' or 'relu'). Determines non-linearity introduced in the model. Values used: ['tanh', 'relu']. Best value: 'tanh'.

solver: Optimization algorithm for weight updates (e.g., 'sgd' or 'adam'). Values used: ['sgd', 'adam']. Best value: 'sgd'.

alpha: L2 penalty (regularization term) to prevent overfitting. Values used: [0.0001, 0.001]. Best value: 0.0001.

learning_rate: Strategy for updating weights ('constant', 'adaptive'). Controls how much weights are adjusted during training. Values used: ['constant', 'adaptive']. Best value: 'adaptive'.

Ensemble Learning¶

After finding the best parameters for each of the models, we moved on to ensemble learning. Ensemble learning is a powerful machine learning technique that combines multiple models to improve predictive performance and robustness. By aggregating the predictions of diverse models, ensemble methods can achieve better accuracy than any single model alone. This approach is particularly effective in addressing issues like overfitting, bias, and variance, making it a valuable tool in complex data environments

In our project we have made use of the voting technique in Ensemble learning. Voting is a common ensemble method where the final prediction is made by combining the predictions of multiple individual models. It is primarily used for classification tasks

Advantages of Ensemble Learning

  • Improved Accuracy: By leveraging multiple models, ensembles can reduce errors and improve prediction accuracy.
  • Robustness: Ensembles are more resilient to noise and outliers, providing stable predictions across diverse datasets.
  • Flexibility: Allows combining various algorithms to exploit their complementary strengths.
  • Reduced Overfitting: Helps mitigate overfitting by balancing the biases of individual models

Results¶

We trained all of our 4 models with their best parameters and applied voting techinique of ensemble learning on these model with an intention of improving our result.

The performance of various machine learning models with hyperparameter tuning is summarized in the table. Each model's accuracy is consistent across training, validation, and test sets. The Random Forest model shows high accuracy, achieving 92.3% on the test set. Logistic Regression maintains steady performance with a test accuracy of 92.0%. The Decision Tree model is similar, with a test accuracy of 92.1%. The MLP (Multilayer Perceptron) exhibits the highest training accuracy at 96.4%, but its test accuracy drops to 90.4%, indicating potential overfitting. The Ensemble Model achieves the highest test accuracy at 92.4%, showing strong generalization capabilities.

The AUC values provide insights into each model's ability to distinguish between classes. The Random Forest model has a high training AUC of 0.931 but drops significantly to 0.644 on the test set, suggesting overfitting. Logistic Regression shows moderate AUC values, with better generalization indicated by a higher test AUC of 0.739 compared to its training AUC. The Decision Tree model consistently has low AUC values, with the lowest test AUC at 0.555. MLP has an excellent training AUC of 0.973, but this drops to 0.670 on the test set, highlighting overfitting issues. The Ensemble Model balances well with a decent test AUC of 0.733, reflecting robustness.

Training and testing times vary significantly among models. The Random Forest requires moderate training time (619 seconds) and very fast testing time. Logistic Regression has a long training time of approximately 1702 seconds. The Decision Tree is the quickest to train at 66 seconds, making it efficient despite lower performance metrics. MLP takes the longest to train (3055 seconds), reflecting its complexity. Surprisingly, the Ensemble Model is extremely efficient, requiring only about 11 seconds for training.

Several unexpected findings emerge from these results:

  • MLP Overfitting: Despite high training accuracy and AUC, MLP's performance drops on unseen data, indicating overfitting.

  • Logistic Regression's Generalization: It shows better generalization capability than expected, with a higher test AUC compared to its training AUC.

  • Ensemble Efficiency: The ensemble model not only achieves the highest test accuracy but also does so with minimal training time, highlighting its effectiveness and efficiency.

These insights can guide further optimization and selection based on specific needs such as accuracy, computational efficiency, and robustness.

Conclusion¶

In summary, we aim to help lenders make better lending decisions and minimize the risk of financial losses. By accurately predicting the probability of loan default, lenders can adjust their lending policies and terms to better serve their customers while reducing the risk of loan defaults. Thus it is essential to have an effective and reliable predictive model pipeline because it can impact the lender's profitability and the borrowers' credit history.

The Ensemble Model stands out as the best performer with a test accuracy of 92.4% and a test AUC of 0.733. This model not only provides robust predictive power but also achieves this with an impressively short training time of approximately 11 seconds, making it both effective and efficient.

Moving forward, our goal is to leverage these insights to build a more robust machine learning pipeline. By potentially integrating neural networks, we aim to further optimize our models for predicting default risk. This will help lenders make informed decisions and support financially vulnerable individuals in accessing loans, contributing positively to the HCDR initiative. Overall, this phase has been productive, and we anticipate further advancements in our next steps.
